{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496877"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:58:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.36,0.09,0.24,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52924"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38318"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1820"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11060"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52924"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously healthy 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 36-hour history of a fatigue, dyspnoea, non-productive cough and right-sided pleuritic chest pain. The pain came on gradually and is worse when she coughs. She had a laparoscopic cholecystectomy one week earlier and was back at work three days later. On examination, she looks well, with a blood pressure of 125/80 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.9\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Pulmonary auscultation findings included a bilateral wheeze, but the rest of the physical examination was unremarkable. Routine bloods are normal, a D-dimer is 0.4 mg/L (\u0026lt;0.5). A chest X-ray was performed and showed bronchial wall thickening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Oral amoxicillin and doxycycline","V-Q scan","CT pulmonary angiogram","Doppler ultrasonography"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with a non-productive cough, normal vital signs, a low-grade fever and chest pain most likely has an acute chest infection, such as acute bronchitis. Acute bronchitis is primarily a clinical diagnosis, however chest X-rays are often performed. Acute bronchitis is most often caused by a viral infection, and self-resolves within 3 weeks. As such, this patient should be managed with \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E and supportive care (e.g. hydration, simple analgesia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough chest pain with a recent history of surgery should alert the physician for the possibility of pulmonary embolism, this patient has a low pretest probability of pulmonary embolism according to Well\u0027s score. Patients with a Well\u0027s score of \u22644 have a low probability of pulmonary embolism, whereas patients with a Well\u0027s core of \u0026gt;4 have a high probability of pulmonary embolism. Patients with a low pretest probability of pulmonary embolism should be followed up with a D-dimer assay. This patient\u0027s Well\u0027s score of 1.5 (due to recent history of surgery) and a D-dimer level of 0.4 mg/L excludes the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin and doxycycline \u003C/strong\u003Eis indicated for mild community-acquired pneumonia. It is unlikely that this patient has pneumonia due to her auscultation and chest X-ray findings. Pneumonia could present with crepitations, bronchial breath sounds or decreased breath sounds if a parapneumonic effusion is present, but it would be unlikely to present with a wheeze. Patients with pneumonia tend to be more unwell than those with acute bronchitis, and often have tachypnoea, tachycardia and a marked fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EV-Q scan\u003C/strong\u003E and\u003Cstrong\u003E CT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E are indicated in patients with a high pretest probability of pulmonary embolism. CT pulmonary angiogram is preferred but V-Q scan may be used if the patient has contraindications to CT pulmonary angiogram (e.g. renal failure) or if CT pulmonary angiogram is unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoppler ultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E of the affected limb may be performed if the patient has clinical features suggesting deep venous thrombosis (DVT). This patient does not have any feature suggesting a DVT.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute bronchitis is a clinical diagnosis that requires supportive management"],"references":["Kearon C, de Wit K, Parpia S, et al. Diagnosis of Pulmonary Embolism with d-Dimer Adjusted to Clinical Probability. N Engl J Med. 2019; 381:2125-34.","Kinkade S, Long NA. Acute Bronchitis. Am Fam Physician. 2016;94(7):560-565."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38318"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17809"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/178